The graph depicts a curve that represents the Central Bank Replacement Rate (CRR) for the US dollar over the past 25 years. It serves as a tool for monetary policy to regulate the money supply and maintain stability in the economy. The CRR has gradually increased over the years, peaking at a high level in 2008 during the Great Recession. Since then, the CRR has been gradually reduced as the economy recovered. However, the curve is still at a relatively high level compared to the previous years, demonstrating the ongoing impact of the global financial crisis.
